		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Post subject:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b></b></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />I think it'd be much better to focus on ways to make the (vastly more capable) OLPC cheaper, and thus more widely available, than to hack up a 25-year-old video game system. Architectural limitations aside, wouldn't the latter require a separate TV for each unit? Along with increasing the overall price, it kind of throws the OLPC's goals for portability, power efficiency, durability, and aesthetics right out the window.
<br />
<br />I think maybe nostalgia is clouding these guys' better judgment. The average household in the poorest third-world countries is still a far cry from the average American household of the 80's, and I don't think giving them a bunch of TVs and Chinese game consoles is going to change much.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
