		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Post subject:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b></b></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />SD cards can be operated with the <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Serial_Peripheral_Interface_Bus" class="postlink">SPI bus</a>, which has four signals:
<br /><ul><li>clock </li><li>host out </li><li>device out </li><li>chip select </li></ul>Three of these map fairly cleanly to NES controller port 2:<br /><ul><li>clock = CLK </li><li>host out = OUT </li><li>device out = D4 </li></ul>
<br />This leaves chip select (/CS) as the major remaining problem. The NES ordinarily leaves both controllers selected at once and clocks one of them at a time. Perhaps the SD interface could reconstruct /CS by requiring the host to clock (read $4017) a few times first.
<br />
<br />The "expansion port", on the other hand, has a few more signals that can be used.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
